r 1355","1333":"1333","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","about 1340":"omkring 1340","Westmorland, England":"Westmorland, England","Bellingham, Northumberland, England":"Bellingham, Northumberland, England"},"nl":{"about 1340–":"circa 1340–Overleden","1333–Female":"1333–Overleden","1360–Male":"1360–Overleden","1340–Male":"1340–Overleden","about 1360":"circa 1360","1455":"1455","before 1355":"vóór 1355","1333":"1333","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","about 1340":"circa 1340","Westmorland, England":"Westmorland, England","Bellingham, Northumberland, England":"Bellingham, Northumberland, England"},"en":{"about 1340–":"about 1340–Deceased","1333–Female":"1333–Deceased","1360–Male":"1360–Deceased","1340–Male":"1340–Deceased","about 1360":"about 1360","1455":"1455","before 1355":"before 1355","1333":"1333","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","about 1340":"about 1340","Westmorland, England":"Westmorland, England","Bellingham, Northumberland, England":"Bellingham, Northumberland, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bellingham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the places called Bellingham, in Greater London (formerly in Kent) and Northumberland. The former is named with Old English <i>Beringahām</i> ‘homestead (Old English <i>hām</i>) of the followers of <i>Be(o)ra</i>’, a byname meaning ‘bear’; the latter seems to have been originally named as the ‘homestead of the dwellers at the bell’, from Old English <i>belle</i> used in a transferred sense of a bell-shaped hill.","History: Richard Bellingham (<i>c.</i> 1592–1672) came from Boston, Lincolnshire, England, to Boston, MA, in 1634. He was a controversial political figure in the new colony, an opponent of John Winthrop (see   Winthrop  ). He was elected governor of MA in 1641 and again in 1654 and 1665–72. — An Irish family of this name trace their descent from William de Bellingham, who was sheriff of Tynedale, Northumbria, in 1279. They were established in Ireland by Robert Bellingham, who settled in County Longford in 1611. They gave their name to Castlebellingham in County Louth, Ireland."],"variants":[{"name":"Winthrop","meanings":["English (Cumberland and Durham): habitational name from any of the places in Lincolnshire and Nottinghamshire called Winthorpe. The former is named with the Old English personal name or byname <i>Wine</i>, meaning ‘friend’, + Old Norse <i>thorp</i> ‘settlement’. The Lincolnshire placename probably derives from the Old English personal name <i>Wine</i> + Old Norse <i>thorp</i> ‘secondary settlement, outlying farmstead’. The Nottinghamshire placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Wīgmund</i> or the Old Norse personal name <i>Vígmundr</i> + Old Norse <i>thorp</i>.","History: John Winthrop (1588–1649) was the first governor of the Massachusetts Bay Colony. He kept a detailed journal, an invaluable source for historians. He was born into a gentry family in Suffolk, England, whose fortunes were founded by his grandfather Adam Winthrop (died 1562) of Lavenham. In 1544 the latter acquired a 500-acre estate that had been part of the monastery of Bury St. Edmunds. John Winthrop was a Puritan who emigrated from Groton, Suffolk, to Salem, MA, in 1630 because of Charles I's anti-Puritan policies. By the time of his death he had had four wives and 16 children, the most notable of whom was his son John (1606–76), a scientist and governor of CT. His descendants were prominent in politics and science, including John Winthrop (1714–79), an astronomer, and Robert Winthrop (1809–94), a senator and speaker of the US House of Representatives."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":42,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":115,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Robert de Bellingham was born about 1340, in Bellingham, Northumberland, England. He married Margaret Burneshead before 1355, in Westmorland, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"about 1340–":"umbes 1340–Surnud","1333–Female":"1333–Surnud","1360–Male":"1360–Surnud","1340–Male":"1340–Surnud","about 1360":"umbes 1360","1455":"1455","before 1355":"enne 1355","1333":"1333","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","about 1340":"umbes 1340","Westmorland, England":"Westmorland, England","Bellingham, Northumberland, England":"Bellingham, Northumberland, England"},"fi":{"about 1340–":"noin 1340–Kuollut","1333–Female":"1333–Kuollut","1360–Male":"1360–Kuollut","1340–Male":"1340–Kuollut","about 1360":"noin 1360","1455":"1455","before 1355":"ennen vuotta 1355","1333":"1333","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","about 1340":"noin 1340","Westmorland, England":"Westmorland, England","Bellingham, Northumberland, England":"Bellingham, Northumberland, England"},"fr":{"about 1340–":"environ 1340–Décédé","1333–Female":"1333–Décédée","1360–Male":"1360–Décédé","1340–Male":"1340–Décédé","about 1360":"environ 1360","1455":"1455","before 1355":"avant 1355","1333":"1333","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","about 1340":"environ 1340","Westmorland, England":"Westmorland, Angleterre","Bellingham, Northumberland, England":"Bellingham, Northumberland, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Robert de Bellingham est né environ 1340, à Bellingham, Northumberland, Angleterre. Il a épousé Margaret Burneshead avant 1355, à Westmorland, Angleterre. Ils ont e